        <section id="intro">
            <h2>Introduction</h2>
            <p>Mathematical modeling involves abstracting reality into simplified forms that are amenable to analysis, allowing for predictions and general principles in biological systems [cite: 1715-1718].</p>
        </section>

        <section id="week1">
            <h2>I. Week 1: Continuous-time population models</h2>
            <p>Population dynamics studies how groups of individuals change over time due to four fundamental processes: births, deaths, immigration, and emigration [cite: 1701-1704].</p>
            <p>The rate of change is expressed by the fundamental differential equation:</p>
            \[ \frac{dN}{dt} = \text{birth rate} - \text{death rate} + \text{immigration rate} - \text{emigration rate} \]
            <p>By solving this equation, we can find the population size \(N(t)\) at any given time[cite: 1705].</p>
        </section>

        <section id="stochastic">
            <h2>II. Probabilistic and Stochastic Modelling</h2>
            <p>Biological systems are inherently stochastic due to the unpredictable timing and outcomes of events like births and deaths[cite: 1724]. This uncertainty can be modeled using three formalisms[cite: 1725]:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Master Equation:</strong> Discrete state space in continuous time, governed by Kolmogorov's forward equation[cite: 1727].</li>
                <li><strong>Fokker-Planck Equation (FPE):</strong> Continuous state space advection-diffusion equation[cite: 1733].</li>
                <li><strong>Stochastic Differential Equations (SDE):</strong> Describes the evolution of individual trajectories with random "kicks" [cite: 1738-1741].</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>The Moran Model</h3>
            <p>A classic population genetics model where population size \(N\) is fixed, and births and deaths are coupled[cite: 1776, 1777]. In a system with two alleles (A and B), the transition rate for a birth of type A is[cite: 1784]:</p>
            \[ T(n+1|n) = \left( \frac{n}{N}\right) \left(\frac{N-n}{N-1} \right) + \mu\left(\frac{N-n}{N} \right) \]
        </section>

        <section id="adaptive">
            <h2>III. Adaptive Dynamics</h2>
            <p>Adaptive Dynamics deals with continuous trait spaces where phenotypic traits (like size or maturation age) vary continuously[cite: 1410, 1411].</p>
            <p>The core of this framework is determining if a mutant strategy \(\theta_m\) can invade a resident population \(\theta_r\)[cite: 1440, 1441]. The "canonical equation" of adaptive dynamics describes the evolutionary trajectory of a trait[cite: 1475]:</p>
            \[ \frac{d\theta}{d\tau} = g(\theta) \]
            <p>In certain eco-evolutionary scenarios, trait substitution can drive a population to extinction, a phenomenon known as <strong>evolutionary suicide</strong>[cite: 1678].</p>
        </section>
